{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504039"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:09:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:09:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2290"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2290"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.06,0.05,0.82,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2290"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108312"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2290"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2290"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90715"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"549"},{"type":"contributions","id":"552"},{"type":"contributions","id":"577"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14206"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40416"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42460"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108312"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for ongoing assessment of his hypertension. He has a medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidaemia. For the last three months, he has been taking hydrochlorothiazide 25 mg daily, in addition to stopping smoking, exercising regularly, and losing weight. His home blood pressure monitoring averages 162/100 mmHg. His only other medication is atorvastatin for hyperlipidaemia. No secondary causes of hypertension have been identified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a blood pressure of 160/98 mmHg and a BMI of 26 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. His pulse rate is 72/min, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.6\u00b0C. The rest of his physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecent biochemistry results reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium: 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium: 3.7 mmol/L (3.5-5.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloride: 103 mmol/L (96-106)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate: 26 mmol/L (22-32)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea: 7 mmol/L (3-9)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 118 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 58 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (\u003E90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase dose of hydrochlorothiazide","Start atenolol","Start spironolactone","Start perindopril","Start prazosin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with uncontrolled hypertension despite three months of treatment with hydrochlorothiazide and lifestyle modifications. The most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Estart perindopril\u003C/strong\u003E, an angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitor. This approach aligns with current guidelines for managing uncomplicated hypertension. In patients with reduced creatinine clearance (\u003C60 mL/min), as in this case with an eGFR of 58 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2, dose reduction of ACE inhibitors should be used and potassium levels should be carefully monitored due to the increased risk of hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the dose of hydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as the first step when initial monotherapy fails to achieve target blood pressure. Adding a second drug from a different class is generally more effective and associated with fewer side effects than increasing the dose of a single agent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting atenolol\u003C/strong\u003E, a beta-blocker, is not ideal in this case. Beta-blockers are no longer recommended as first-line or second-line agents for uncomplicated hypertension due to their less favorable efficacy and safety profile compared to other antihypertensive medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting spironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate at this stage. While it can be useful in treatment-resistant hypertension, it is not recommended as a second-line agent, especially in a patient with mildly impaired renal function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting prazosin\u003C/strong\u003E, an alpha-blocker, is also not recommended as a second-line agent for hypertension. Alpha-blockers can cause postural hypotension and are generally reserved for specific indications or when other options have failed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe current guidelines for hypertension management recommend ACE inhibitors, angiotensin receptor blockers (ARBs), calcium channel blockers, and thiazide diuretics as suitable first-line antihypertensive medications. When the initial agent fails to achieve target blood pressure after three months, adding a second drug from a different class is recommended. This approach provides better blood pressure control while minimizing the risk of adverse effects associated with high doses of a single agent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the current Australian guidelines for hypertension management (2016), blood pressure targets should be individualised through shared decision-making between patient and clinician, taking into account the potential benefits and harms of treatment, and reviewed regularly. In general, a target blood pressure of \u003C140/90 mmHg is recommended for patients with uncomplicated hypertension. In patients at high of cardiovascular risk\u2014such as those with previous myocardial infarction or stroke, diabetes with microalbuminuria, moderate to severe CKD (as in this patient with eGFR 58 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E) or familial hypercholesterolaemia\u2014more intensive systolic blood pressure targets (\u003C120 mmHg) may be appropriate. However, such targets require careful monitoring for treatment-related adverse effects, including hypotension, syncope, electrolyte disturbances, and acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["If, after three months of antihypertensive therapy for uncomplicated hypertension, the target for blood pressure control is not reached, a second drug from a different pharmacological class should be added to the regimen.","ACE inhibitors, ARBs, calcium channel blockers, and thiazide diuretics are all suitable first-line antihypertensive medications for uncomplicated hypertension.","Blood pressure target for patients with uncomplicated hypertension should be \u003C140/90 mmHg, with lower targets potentially conferring improved cardiovascular outcomes if tolerated."],"references":["Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults 2016. In: National Heart Foundation of Australia [online]. Available at: https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/getmedia/c83511ab-835a-4fcf-96f5-88d770582ddc/PRO-167_Hypertension-guideline-2016_WEB.pdf","Gabb GM, Mangoni AA, Anderson CS, Cowley D, Dowden JS, Golledge J, et al. Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults - 2016. Med J Aust. 2016;205(2):85-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27456450/","Taler SJ. Initial Treatment of Hypertension. New England Journal of Medicine. 2018;378(7):636-44. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMcp1613481","Atkins ER, Perkovic V. Blood pressure: at what level is treatment worthwhile?. Aust Prescr 2019;42:127-30. Available at: https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2019.038"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90715"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2290"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90715"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-09T15:41:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-24T15:02:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2290"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108312"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedA